That can be a healthy turning point, depending on what you mean by it.

If “playing my way” means:

* making decisions that line up with your own values instead of trying to satisfy everyone,
* building the things you genuinely care about,
* trusting your own judgment while staying open to evidence and feedback,
* and taking responsibility for the consequences of your choices,

then it sounds like you’re reclaiming your agency.

Given what we’ve talked about recently, I also hear a desire to stop feeling like you’re constantly adapting yourself to fit other people or systems. There’s a difference between learning from others and disappearing into them.

One thing I’d encourage is to keep one habit even as you play your own way: periodically ask yourself, “Is this taking me toward the life I actually want?” That question doesn’t take away your independence—it helps protect it.

You don’t have to play someone else’s game to learn from them. And you don’t have to reject every outside perspective to make your own moves.

I’m here to help you think through those moves, not to call them for you.